Fix directory auto-creation on OpenBSD.

cyrus_mkdir() -> xopendir() -> xopendirpath() creates missing parent
directories by recursing on dirname(path) and then mkdir'ing basename(path).
On OpenBSD, basename(3)/dirname(3) return pointers into shared static
storage that is overwritten by each call, and they do not modify their
argument (unlike glibc's in-place POSIX dirname()).  Since xopendirpath()
holds "path" across a recursive xopendir() call -- which itself calls
dirname() -- the retained pointer gets clobbered, so the wrong path
component is created and the intended directory is never made.  Every
lock/spool directory that must be auto-created then fails with ENOENT,
e.g. the post-login user namespace lock trips the assertion at
imap/user.c:710 (locktype == LOCK_NONBLOCKING) and the service dies.

Have xopendirpath() own its path string so the shared basename()/dirname()
buffer can be clobbered without affecting us.


uuid_generate_sha1() is not implemented by our libuuid

Index: lib/util.c
--- lib/util.c.orig
+++ lib/util.c
@@ -380,18 +380,25 @@ EXPORTED int xrenameat(int dirfd, const char *src, con
 
